1. Data Analysis Intro¶

Data Analysis¶

Why¶

  • Get useful information from data
  • Better understand your customers, business, politics, nature, ...
  • Make better decisions

How¶

  • Wrangle data
  • Explore data
  • Communicate insights

Data Analysis Application Examples¶

  • Netflix: personalized movie recommendations
  • Facebook: news feed ranking
  • Walmart: find out what to stock in their stores
  • Sports: analyzing and predicting performance
  • Pharmaceutical research: find chemicals compounds that are likely to make effective pharmaceutical drugs

Data Analysis Process¶

  • Questions
    • What do you want to find out?
  • Wrangle: gather, assess, and clean data
    • Collect data
    • Assess for problems in data quality or structure
    • Clean by modifying/converting/removing data
  • Explore: Perform Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
    • Find patterns
    • Visualize relationships
    • Build intuition about the data
  • Draw conclusions
    • Statistics
    • Machine Learning (outside of scope here)
  • Communicate
    • Share and explain your findings and insights
    • Reports, slides, blog posts, emails, conversations

2. Jupyter Notebooks¶

What are Jupyter Notebooks¶

  • Web application
  • Jupyter notebooks
    • can be viewed and edited in the browser
    • are a form of literate programming where documentation is written along with the code. Donald Knuth:

      Instead of imagining that our main task is to instruct a computer what to do, let us concentrate rather on explaining to human beings what we want a computer to do.

    • combine text, math expressions, code, and plots in one document
    • support multiple programming languages, including Python

Jupyter Notebook Contents¶

  • Markdown cells
    • text: Markdown
    • math expressions: LaTeX
  • Code cells
    • code: here, we use Python
    • visualization: plots

Jupyter Notebook Demo¶

3. Case Study¶

Case Study: GDP per capita and democracy index of countries¶

  • Question: how does the wealth of a country (measured by its GDP per capita) correlate with its regime type (measured by its democracy index)

  • A project I did in the Udacity nanodegree program Data Analyst

  • Also published on GitHub, and can be viewed online with nbviewer.
  • Data sets:
    • GDP per capita
    • democracy index
    • total population
    • fuel exports
  • Available under the CC BY 4.0 from:
    • www.gapminder.org
    • World Bank Open Data

Backup: Spurious correlations¶

  • In a spurious correlation (or spurious relationship) events/variables are associated but not causally related
  • Possible reasons:
    • Common factor (lurking variable)
    • Coincidence
  • An example found here: divorce rate in the Maine and per capita consumption of margarine.
